abstract: This congressional race in Washington State shows the November elections in microcosm.
snippet: This congressional race in Washington State shows the November elections in microcosm.
lead_paragraph: VANCOUVER, Wash. — In March, five months before he became the Republican nominee in a Washington State congressional race, Joe Kent appeared on a webcast hosted by a Gen-Z white nationalist group called the American Populist Union. Kent, who would soon be endorsed by Donald Trump, was there to explain his disavowal of Nick Fuentes, a smirking 24-year-old far-right influencer whom The New York Times has described as “a prominent white supremacist.”

main: The Midterm Race That Has It All
print_headline: To Understand The Midterms, Meet Joe and Marie

lead_paragraph: SKELETONS, by Deborah Landau. (Copper Canyon, paperback, $18.) Landau’s earthy, angsty poems — about sex and mortality and cosmic despair — are insistently quotable, and more fun than they have any right to be. One opens with a line Emily Dickinson might have written, had she been on Twitter: “Sorry not sorry, said death.”

abstract: Chileans are debating how to rewrite the nation’s Constitution to address their society’s most stubborn problems.
snippet: Chileans are debating how to rewrite the nation’s Constitution to address their society’s most stubborn problems.
lead_paragraph: SANTIAGO, Chile — Writing a new Constitution strikes many Americans as a transgressive idea. Our Constitution is the oldest in the world, and it has come to seem immutable. The last really substantive change was a 1971 amendment lowering the voting age to 18. Instead of updating a text written more than 200 years ago, Americans have come to rely on the imaginations of nine justices who decide what they think it should say.

main: The Founders of a Nation Should Not Have the Last Word
print_headline: The Founders Should Not Have the Last Word

lead_paragraph: An article on Sunday about Turkey’s detention of building contractors as the earthquake death toll grows misstated the action taken by the Turkish government against more than 100 contractors in connection to buildings that collapsed in Monday’s earthquake. abstract: Griner, speaking to reporters as she prepares for her next basketball season in the W.N.B.A., said she would continue to fight for those considered wrongfully detained by Russia, like the journalist Evan Gershkovich.
snippet: Griner, speaking to reporters as she prepares for her next basketball season in the W.N.B.A., said she would continue to fight for those considered wrongfully detained by Russia, like the journalist Evan Gershkovich.
lead_paragraph: PHOENIX — Brittney Griner, the W.N.B.A. star who became the center of a geopolitical showdown between the United States and Russia last year, said Thursday that her management team has been in touch with the family of Evan Gershkovich, a Wall Street Journal reporter detained in Russia and classified by the U.S. government as a wrongful detainee.

abstract: Lawmakers in the House have yet to be sworn in. They can’t help constituents or get classified briefings, much less hold hearings or pass laws. And at some point, they may have trouble getting paid.
snippet: Lawmakers in the House have yet to be sworn in. They can’t help constituents or get classified briefings, much less hold hearings or pass laws. And at some point, they may have trouble getting paid.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The personal and political drama that is playing out on the House floor as Representative Kevin McCarthy tries and fails repeatedly to become speaker has broader implications for the country, raising questions about what happens when one chamber of the legislative branch ceases to function.

main: Lacking a Speaker, One Part of Government Ceases to Function
print_headline: With No Leader Chosen, House Grinds to a Halt
